Then,rename conditions and reshape to longer format

The next strp is useing pivot_longer()function to transfer from wild format to longer format.It should be using the tidyr package within the tidyverse.Another code common to use is %>%, which means pipe. In tidyverse, pipe usually used for data manipulations.The most easy way is to use pivot_longer()function to reshape the fromat from wild to long first. Then, use recode() function with factors could change the value, but also preserve the existing order of levels .Also, you can use recode_factor(), it helps to change the order of levels to match the order of replacements.Another function you may use below is mutate()function, which is used to create a new variable from a data set.

assignment_long_data <- assignment_1_data %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(Condition1, Condition2, Condition3, Condition4),
               names_to = "Condition",
               values_to = "RT")
long_rename_data <- assignment_long_data %>%
  mutate(Condition = recode(Condition,
                            "Condition1" = "Number_Number",
                            "Condition2" = "Number_Letter",
                            "Condition3" = "Letter_Number",
                            "Condition4" = "Letter_Letter"))

summary data and create a gt table

The next step is to summary data first. Use group_by()functioin use to group the dataframe. Summarise() function is used on grouped data created by group_by(), it is very useful with data has been grouped by one or more variables.Common to use summarise() with mean() which is calculated by taking the sum of the values and dividing with the number of values in a data series; median() which means the middle number of the dataset is ordered from smallest to largest; sd() which compute the standard deviation of given values; etc.

After done the summaise, use gt package is easy to make a table, which could conveys the needed information better. The tab_header()function means you are able to add a title or/and subtitle to gt table. fmt_markdown() function helps to tansform to the approprite output type for markdown formate.

long_rename_data %>%
  group_by(Condition) %>%
  summarise(Mean=mean(RT),
            SD=sd(RT),
            Median=median(RT),
            Min=min(RT),
            Max=max(RT)) %>%
  gt() %>%
  tab_header( title = "Summary Table for conditions") %>%
  fmt_markdown(columns = c(Condition))%>%
  fmt_markdown(columns = c(Mean))%>%
  fmt_markdown(columns = c(Median))%>%
  fmt_markdown(columns = c(SD))%>%
  fmt_markdown(columns = c(Min)) %>%
  fmt_markdown(columns = c(Max))

Now, lets start the Data visualization

This is my first plots,which I use the point plot to have a general view.Most common one to use is str_to_title() function which helps to convert the first letter for everyword to be Uppercase, and others all be lower case. Also, geom_point()function use to creats a scatterplot in ggplot package.

# Point plot
long_rename_data %>%
  mutate(Condition = str_to_title(Condition)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = ID, y=RT, color= Condition))+
  labs(title = "Participant's reaction time",
       x = "Participants",
       y = "Reaction Time")+
  geom_point(na.rm = TRUE)

Lets seperete the point plot under the difference condition.

We may have a view due to the last plot, but we may would like to have a clear view for each conditions. Therefore,we can use facet_wrap() funtion seperete by each conditions. facet_wrap() function able to wrap a 1d sequence of panels into 2d. ggplot()is a powerful and flexible package for r, you can use ggplot to control the mapping from data to aesthetics. geom_jitter()funtion will add small mount of random variiation to the location for each point, it is helpful to handling overplotting situation which caused by discreteness in some too small datasets. theme_minimal()function means a minimalistic theme without any backgroud.

long_rename_data %>%
  mutate(Condition = str_to_title(Condition)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = ID, y=RT, color= Condition))+
  geom_jitter(width = .2)+
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(text = element_text(size=10))+
  labs(title = "Participant's reaction time under the difference condintions",
       x = "Participants",
       y = "Reaction Time")+
  guides(color='none')+
  facet_wrap(~Condition)

Now, lets start with the density plots. I Put 4 density plots below with difference code and packages.

Lets start with the basic one which is the histogram. geom_histogram()function is common to use in ggplot package, and it dispaly the counts with bars.

long_rename_data%>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = RT))+
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(fill = Condition))+
  labs(title = "Histogram of Reaction Time by density",
       x = "Reaction time",
       y = "Density")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

You may want to get the more direct information from each condition, therefore, we can use the facet_wrap()again to seperet conditions. geom_density() function is able to compute and draw kernel density estimate, Is much easier to read each condition now, right?

long_rename_data %>%
  mutate(Condition = str_to_title(Condition)) %>%
  group_by(Condition) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= RT, fill = Condition))+
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..))+
  geom_density(aes(y=..density..))+
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(text = element_text(size=10))+
  guides(fill='none')+
  labs(title = "Effect of difference conditions on Reaction Time",
       x = "Reaction Time",
       y = "Density")+
  facet_wrap(~ Condition)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Based on we learned how to use geom_density()funtion, we may able to use in a new plots, it is very similar to the first density plot, riht? Due to the alpha in geom_point, which refers to the opacity of geom,you may feel this one is much earier to read. The alpha value from 0 to 1, lower values corresponding to more transparent colors. Therefore, if alpha=0, which means it is transparent, and if alpha=1, it should be opaque.

long_rename_data %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(
    x=RT,
    color = Condition,
    fill = Condition))+
  geom_density(alpha=0.3)+
  labs(title = "Density of Reaction time",
       x= "Reaction Time",
       y= "Density")

Now, we may able try the ggridges package amd use the geom_density_rides()function to creating a ridgeline plot. A numerical variabe and a categorical variable a density estimation of date, you could calculated and display for each group and get a ridgeline plot.

long_rename_data %>%
  mutate(Condition=str_to_title(Condition)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = RT, y = fct_reorder(Condition,.fun = mean, RT)))+
  geom_density_ridges(aes(fill = Condition))+
  theme_minimal()+
  theme(text = element_text(size = 10)) +
  guides(fill = 'none') + 
  labs(title = "Density of Reation time in difference conditions",
       x = "Reaction Time",
       y = NULL)
## Picking joint bandwidth of 10.6

Now, lets move to the boxplot.

This boxplot also used by ggplot, geom_violin() function help you to make a violin plot; and the geom_boxplot()function is the code help you to make a box plot. Normally, there will be other two code also common to use in box-plot. The first one is box_plot, which help you to aviod rewriting code each time when you add some new informtion. Another one is coord_flip() which help to flip the side of the graph.

long_rename_data %>% 
  filter(!is.na(Condition ) & !is.na(RT)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Condition, y = RT, color = Condition)) + 
  geom_violin() +
  geom_jitter(alpha = .2, width = .1) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = .5) +
  guides(colour = 'none') + 
  labs(title = "Examining the effect of conditions on Reaction time", 
       x = "Conditions", 
       y = "Reaction time")

My last plot to combine previous plots in one and create a scatter plot

This plot require to install the cowplot package, ggpubr package and ggstatsplot package at the beginning. There are several new code that I use in this plot. xlab= means the x-axis lable, and ylab=means y-axis lable.margin.plot()function means the graphing the result from the margin. Therefore, this scatter plot helps you get more information that you need just from one plot.

ggscatterhist(long_rename_data,
                group = "Condition", 
                x = "ID",
                y = "RT",
                xlab = "Participants",
                ylab = "Reaction time",
                color = "Condition", 
                margin.plot = "histogram",
                marginal = TRUE,
                centrality.para = "mean",
                margin.params = list(fill = "Condition",
                                     color = "black",
                                     size = .2),
                title = "Scatter plot for participants and reaction time")
